The given solution demonstrates how to perform long division in base 4, which is similar to the process in base 10. The key insight is to recognize that the digits and arithmetic operations follow the rules of base 4 instead of base 10.
1. Set up the long division in base 4:
   $$
   \begin{array}{cc|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & & \\
   \cline{3-6}
   1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & & \downarrow \\
   \end{array}
   $$

2. Divide $11_4$ into the leftmost digits of $1023_4$ ($10_4$) and write the result ($3_4$) above the line:
   $$
   \begin{array}{cc|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 3 & \\
   \cline{3-6}
   1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 3&3& \downarrow \\ \cline{4-5}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 0&3& \\
   \end{array}
   $$
   Note that $11_4 \cdot 3_4 = 33_4$ in base 4.

3. Subtract $33_4$ from $102_4$ and bring down the next digit ($3_4$):
   $$
   \begin{array}{cc|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 3 & \\
   \cline{3-6}
   1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 3&3& \downarrow \\ \cline{4-5}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 0&3&3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & & \\
   \end{array}
   $$

4. Divide $11_4$ into $033_4$ and write the result ($3_4$) above the line:
   $$
   \begin{array}{cc|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 3 & 3 \\
   \cline{3-6}
   1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 3&3& \downarrow \\ \cline{4-5}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 0&3&3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & 3&3 \\ \cline{5-6}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & & 0 \\
   \end{array}
   $$

5. The long division is complete, and the quotient is $33_4$.
